arXiv.abstract:
We consider the time-dependence of a hierarchy of scaled $L^{2m}$-norms $D_{m,\omega}$ and $D_{m,	heta}$ of the vorticity $ oldsymbol {\omega} =  oldsymbol{
abla} 	imes {\mathbf u}$ and the density gradient $ oldsymbol{
abla} 	heta$, where $	heta=\log (ho^*/ho^*_0)$, in a buoyancy-driven turbulent flow as simulated by \cite{LR2007}. $ho^*({\mathbf x},\,t) $ is the composition density of a mixture of two incompressible miscible fluids with fluid densities $ho^*_2 > ho^*_1$ and $ho^*_{0}$ is a reference normalisation density. Using data from the publicly available Johns Hopkins Turbulence Database we present evidence that the $L^{2}$-spatial average of the density gradient $ oldsymbol{
abla} 	heta$ can reach extremely large values, even in flows with low Atwood number $At = (ho^*_{2} - ho^*_{1})/(ho^*_{2} + ho^*_{1}) = 0.05$, implying that very strong mixing of the density field at small scales can arise in buoyancy-driven turbulence. This large growth raises the possibility that the density gradient $ oldsymbol{
abla} 	heta$ might blow up in a finite time.
